&lt;p id="QC5bvW"&gt;Leica’s Q series of full-frame compact cameras have had the same 28mm f/1.7 lens since &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2015/6/10/8754047/leica-q-camera-announcement-price-hands-on-launch"&gt;the original in 2015&lt;/a&gt;, but now the company is shaking things up. The Leica Q3 43 launching today is nearly identical to the 60-megapixel &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2023/5/25/23736639/leica-q3-camera-28mm-fixed-lens-compact-8k-availability-price-specs"&gt;Q3&lt;/a&gt;, but it’s got a 43mm f/2 lens for a tighter field of view that’s more appropriate for close-ups and portraits — and, of course, it’s even more expensive, coming in at $6,895 compared to the $6,295 standard model.&lt;/p&gt;
